A new science
In this summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers met to ponder the necessity of a new science that could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
Given the context and maintaining consistency, the translation is:
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Secondly, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, it is widely believed that the most difficult part of the work would lie in utilizing already known natural laws for the benefit of humanity with the help of new technologies.
Who could deny that?
The models of today do work.
A growing group of scientists points out phenomena that are not so easily explainable with today's theories.
These problems, while becoming more frequent, are also elegantly circumvented because the science with which to explain these problems simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
The knowledge in individual scientific disciplines is fairly well established.
At least the part of physics that we as ordinary people encounter is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not understand, it is assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Moreover, there are the new social sciences that focus on people and societies.
In each of these areas—physics, biochemistry, and social sciences—the theories are established and mostly stand without dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and mechanisms.
In very rare cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field, as these worlds and languages are fundamentally different.
This means that we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the inclusion of multiple disciplines.
For example, consider the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs based on the principles of physics. The information transmitted during this process is conveyed according to the laws of electricity.
Additionally, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and convey information in the process.
During the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: Here, information is exchanged through language, symbols, and ideas.
At every level, it involves the exchange of information and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes at each level.
Information is exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that even begins to explain this information exchange.
To address this gap, some scientists have tried to redefine the toolkit for explaining processes within one level and then apply it to another level.
These attempts then result in something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works well, but the fundamental problem is not solved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels and how is it transmitted?
Now almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from various countries and fields and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from relevant disciplines, artists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also participating in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," where the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and extended to another.
And others believe that a completely new approach is required.
In your opinion, many scientific norms are the product of historical coincidences, and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS Group is lucky, new radical approaches may emerge from scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Complete freedom of thought is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities bearing the sign of "science" have developed, similar to their counterparts in the world of business, an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries must build similar resources as industrial nations. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas originate from laboratories and research centers that are not connected to the major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where computer capacities were scarce at best.
The most groundbreaking and literally world-shaking insights in the field of physics over the last decades did not come as expected from the known innovation hubs, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has provided cognitive scientists with important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, he changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unexpected start of an attempt to redefine the universe in this manner.
These gaps have been identified for which explanations must be found.
Further scientists from innovative regions will be included in this group to identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, as it were.
And the most innovative new concepts in the field of information science, which the FIS group refers to as "transplantation strategies," come today from various decentralized networks around the globe.
